                                    <watches>3</watches>
                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13451431" author="thobbs" created="Sat, 8 Sep 2012 22:49:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Attached patch changes the color option to accept a choice of &lt;tt&gt;always&lt;/tt&gt;, &lt;tt&gt;never&lt;/tt&gt;, or &lt;tt&gt;auto&lt;/tt&gt;, defaulting to &lt;tt&gt;auto&lt;/tt&gt;, which uses colors if not reading from a file and stdout is connected to a terminal (at least as well as we can detect that).  I based the options off of &lt;tt&gt;ls&lt;/tt&gt; and &lt;tt&gt;grep&lt;/tt&gt;, which use the same format.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13451443" author="thepaul" created="Sun, 9 Sep 2012 00:13:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Since I&apos;m not a particular fan of ls/grep&apos;s command-line color control (too much typing for cases which are fairly common) and since this isn&apos;t backwards compatible (using &lt;tt&gt;&amp;#45;-color&lt;/tt&gt; alone will give an error), I&apos;m inclined to vote -1 on it. Can we just add a &lt;tt&gt;&amp;#45;-no-color&lt;/tt&gt; option to force color off for the people who don&apos;t want to do &lt;tt&gt;TERM=dumb&lt;/tt&gt; or &lt;tt&gt;cqlsh | cat&lt;/tt&gt; or something?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13451816" author="slebresne" created="Mon, 10 Sep 2012 08:36:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t have any problem with ls/grep&apos;s command-line color control but I would tend to agree that it&apos;s probably not worth breaking any backward compatibility and a --no-color would be good enough. I don&apos;t care much about the matter though, just my 2 cents.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13452288" author="thobbs" created="Mon, 10 Sep 2012 18:37:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;v2 patch adds a &lt;tt&gt;&amp;#45;&amp;#45;no-color&lt;/tt&gt; option instead.  The behavior now is that with &lt;tt&gt;&amp;#45;&amp;#45;color&lt;/tt&gt;, color will always be enabled, with &lt;tt&gt;&amp;#45;&amp;#45;no-color&lt;/tt&gt;, it will always be disabled, and without either one, the behavior is similar to &lt;tt&gt;auto&lt;/tt&gt;, where color is only enabled if not reading a file and stdout is connected to a terminal.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13452330" author="thepaul" created="Mon, 10 Sep 2012 19:12:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13452393" author="brandon.williams" created="Mon, 10 Sep 2012 20:07:42 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Committed.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
